e (Sources 22185). Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow is present.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_014"], "suggestions": ["Replace rxn_014 with a plausible route to succinaldehyde, e.g., from succinate reduction or butanediol oxidation", "Alternatively, introduce an intermediate reduction step using mineral-surface Fe0 or FeS", "Consider using a crotonaldehyde intermediate from acetaldehyde aldol followed by reduction"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.7, "rxn_013": 0.85, "rxn_014": 0.35, "rxn_015": 0.8, "rxn_016": 0.8, "rxn_017": 0.8}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.58, "pathway_coherence": 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.8, "target_achievement": 0.62, "overall_confidence": 0.65, "feedback": "Full CO2-origin version of P5 with good environmental flow from hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface chemistry to biochemical hydrolysis. Inherits the rxn_014 problem. The upstream hydrothermal steps (rxn_001, rxn_002) improve the environmental story.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_014"], "suggestions": ["Fix rxn_014 as suggested for P5", "This would become one of the strongest pathways if the succinaldehyde formation step were corrected"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_006": 0.65, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_018": 0.8, "rxn_019": 0.5, "rxn_009": 0.8, "rxn_010": 0.45, "rxn_011": 0.85, "rxn_012": 0.55}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.55, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.78, "target_achievement": 0.55, "overall_confidence": 0.6, "feedback": "Fe2+-catalyzed protometabolic route. rxn_018 (pyruvate carboxylation to OAA) is well-supported by literature (Sources 9400). However, rxn_019 has a carbon balance issue: OAA (C4) + acetaldehyde (C2) = C6, but \u03b1-KG is C5, requiring CO2 loss that isn't mechanistically justified as a simple aldol. rxn_010 selective carboxylate-to-aldehyde reduction remains the hardest step in the biological analog portion. The Fe2+ catalysis theme is a