": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Delta-1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Proline aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-Hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate (HKG)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3COO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on the greigite surface. H2 dissociates on FeNiS sites. Hydride transfer to CO2 produces formate (HCOO-). This mirrors the first step of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway catalyzed by formate dehydrogenase, whose active site resembles greigite.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on iron-sulfur minerals is one of the best-characterized prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Greigite (Fe3S4) is a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters and catalyzes this reaction under hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This is the entry point for all carbon into the network. Sources 9400 describe Fe2+-catalyzed reactions producing key metabolic precursors at 70\u00b0C.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite with Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal, rock-water interactions, strongly reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is reduced to formaldehyde via 2-electron reduction. Fe0 acts as the electron donor, being oxidized to Fe2+. Magnetite surface provides the catalytic platform for H-transfer. HCOO- + 2[H] \u2192 CH2O + H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction of formate to formaldehyde on magnetite surfaces has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom et al., 1999; He et al., 2019). Fe0 provides the thermodynamic driving force. Formaldehyde is an essential C1 building block. Sources 2595 require formaldehyde concentrations of ~30 mM for amino acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate carboxylation to glyoxylate on iron minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent, CO2-rich fluids mixing with H2-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate undergoes carboxylation via CO2 insertion on the pyrite surface. The activated C1 formate attacks CO2 to form the C2 \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate (OHCCOOH). FeS clusters provide electron density to activate CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a key C2 \u03b1-keto acid required for the HKG cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017; Sources 10738). Pyrite-mediated carboxylation reactions have been proposed in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (Wachtershauser, 1988). CO2 fixation into C-C bonds on metal sulfide surfaces is a core feature of hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reductive fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite + magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"3 CO2 + 4 H2 \u2192 pyruvate + 3 H2O; alkaline vent, native iron present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on greigite/magnetite surfaces. CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO (or formyl intermediate) \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate via further CO2 insertion. Each step involves H2-driven reduction on the mineral surface. Net: 3CO2 + 4H2 \u2192 CH3COCOOH + 3H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct CO2-to-pyruvate synthesis on iron minerals has been demonstrated by Varma et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019). Greigite provides the catalytic surface mimicking the acetyl-CoA pathway. This is a cornerstone of the 'metabolism-first' hypothesis. Sources 9400 describe Fe2+-catalyzed formation of metabolic precursors including pyruvate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate to acetate on greigite (acetyl-CoA pathway analog)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (FeNiS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"2 HCOO- + 2 H2 \u2192 CH3COO- + 2 H2O; Wood-Ljungdahl analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formate molecules undergo reductive coupling on greigite surface. First formate is reduced to a methyl group, second is reduced to CO, then carbonyl insertion forms the acetyl group which is hydrolyzed to acetate. 2HCOO- + 2H2 \u2192 CH3COO- + OH- + H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetate synthesis from CO2/formate on FeNiS minerals mimics the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020; Herschy et al., 2014). This provides an alternative C2 building block feeding into pyruvate synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate carboxylation to pyruvate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite with Fe0 reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CH3COO- + CO2 + 2[H] \u2192 CH3COCOO- + H2O; reductive carboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetate undergoes reductive carboxylation at the methyl C-H bond. CO2 inserts via a metal-carboxylate intermediate on the pyrite surface. Fe0 provides electrons for the reductive activation. Product is pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive carboxylation of acetate to pyruvate on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed as a key step in the reverse/reductive TCA cycle analog (Wachtershauser, 1990; Muchowska et al., 2019). Sources 9400 report Fe2+-catalyzed formation of pyruvate-related intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"\u03b1-KG decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acid; C5 \u2192 C4 + CO2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (HOOC-CO-CH2-CH2-COOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the C1 position adjacent to the keto group. The \u03b2-keto acid motif facilitates loss of CO2, yielding succinic semialdehyde (OHC-CH2-CH2-COOH). Pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is well-established in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures. This is the non-enzymatic analog of the \u03b1-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase reaction. In biology, this produces succinyl-CoA; prebiotically, the product is succinic semialdehyde. The \u03b2-keto acid decarboxylation is thermodynamically favorable (Guzman & Martin, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinic semialdehyde reduction to succinaldehyde on Fe0\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"OHC-CH2-CH2-COOH + 2[H] \u2192 OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO + H2O; carboxylate reduction on native iron\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Succinic semialdehyde adsorbs on the Fe0 surface via the carboxylate group. Fe0 donates 2 electrons and H+ is provided by water. The carboxylate is reduced through a hemiacetal-like intermediate to the aldehyde. Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ provides the thermodynamic driving force (\u0394G << 0 for Fe0 oxidation). Net: RCOOH + 2[H] \u2192 RCHO + H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carboxylate reduction to aldehyde is thermodynamically challenging in solution but becomes feasible on Fe0 surfaces due to the highly negative reduction potential of Fe0/Fe2+ (-0.44 V). Fe0 is present in hydrothermal systems from meteoritic iron and serpentinization products. Carboxylate reduction on metal surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been discussed by Huber & Wachtershauser (2006) and is thermodynamically driven by the strong reducing capacity of native iron. This is the rate-limiting step of the proline aminonitrile pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde-HCN coupling to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to slightly basic pH; cyanohydrin formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of CN- to formaldehyde carbonyl. HCN deprotonates in slightly basic conditions to give CN-, which attacks CH2O to form glycolonitrile (HOCH2CN). Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants via adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN is a well-established prebiotic reaction and is central to the cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016). Sources 9376, 16400 identify glycolonitrile as a critical precursor in prebiotic amino acid synthesis. This is one of the most robust prebiotic reactions known.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile hydrolysis and amination to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution, NH3 present; nitrile hydrolysis + aminonitrile pathway\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolonitrile (HOCH2CN) undergoes aminolysis: NH3 displaces OH to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN). Subsequent hydrolysis of the nitrile group (CN \u2192 CONH2 \u2192 COOH) yields glycine. Montmorillonite catalyzes the hydrolysis step. This is a modified Strecker pathway where the aminonitrile intermediate is formed via the glycolonitrile route.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The glycolonitrile-to-glycine pathway via aminonitrile intermediates is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376, 16400, 6942). The Strecker reaction (aldehyde + NH3 + HCN \u2192 amino acid) is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Sources 6940, 21189). Montmorillonite facilitates hydrolysis and concentrates reactants (Sources 9431).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Classical Strecker: CH2O + NH3 + HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 hydrolysis \u2192 glycine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Formaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form the imine H2C=NH. Step 2: HCN adds to the imine to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN). Step 3: Nitrile hydrolysis in water yields glycine. CH2O + NH3 + HCN + H2O \u2192 H2NCH2COOH + NH3 (regenerated from HCN hydrolysis byproduct).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the most well-characterized prebiotic amino acid formation reactions (Miller, 1953; Strecker, 1850; Sources 6940, 6942, 21189, 10835). It has been demonstrated under a variety of simulated prebiotic conditions including spark discharge experiments, hydrothermal fluids, and surface evaporitic pools. The direct Strecker route to glycine from CH2O is the simplest and most robust pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type aldol to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2 or borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO; base-catalyzed formose reaction first step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The Cannizzaro disproportionation provides the initial enolizable species. Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals act as base. Borate stabilizes the glycolaldehyde product against further aldol reactions by forming borate esters. 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a classic prebiotic reaction (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products and prevent tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004; Sources reference formose reaction with borate). This provides C2 aldehyde building blocks for further synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde oxidation to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV photocatalytic oxidation; HOCH2CHO \u2192 OHCCOOH + 2[H]; anoxic but UV-driven\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO2 absorbs UV light generating electron-hole pairs. The hole oxidizes glycolaldehyde at the alcohol group: HOCH2CHO \u2192 OHC-COOH (glyoxylate). Under anoxic conditions, Fe3+ or the TiO2 hole serves as the terminal electron acceptor. This provides a surface-environment route to glyoxylate complementing the hydrothermal carboxylation route (rxn_003).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic oxidation of organic molecules under UV irradiation is well-established in prebiotic surface chemistry. Early Earth lacked an ozone layer, providing intense UV for photocatalysis. This provides a convergent route to glyoxylate (also formed hydrothermally in rxn_003), creating a key convergence point in the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol to 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate (HKG)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite; Fe2+ in solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CH3COCOO- (C3) + OHCCOO- (C2) \u2192 HKG (C5); aldol condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate (C3) and glyoxylate (C2) undergo aldol condensation. The enolizable methyl group of pyruvate attacks the aldehyde of glyoxylate. This forms 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate (HKG, C5), the signature intermediate of the HKG cycle. Fe2+ or montmorillonite Lewis acid sites catalyze the aldol. Carbon balance: C3 + C2 = C5 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This aldol condensation is the central reaction of the Hydroxy Ketoglutarate (HKG) cycle demonstrated by Muchowska et al. (2017, 2019) and described in Sources 10738, 10732, 9988. The HKG cycle provides a prebiotically plausible analog of the TCA cycle. Pyruvate + glyoxylate \u2192 HKG is one of the most robust prebiotic C-C bond forming reactions, with proper C3 + C2 = C5 stoichiometry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"HKG dehydration/reduction to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ in solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"HKG \u2192 \u03b1-KG via dehydration then reduction of double bond; Fe2+ as electron source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"4-Hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate undergoes dehydration to form 2-oxoglutaconate (elimination of H2O from the 3,4-hydroxyl). Then the resulting double bond is reduced by Fe2+-donated electrons (or H2) to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Net: HKG + 2[H] \u2192 \u03b1-KG + H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The conversion of HKG to \u03b1-KG via dehydration-reduction is part of the HKG cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017, 2019; Sources 10738). Fe2+ serves as the electron donor for the reduction step, consistent with the Fe2+-catalyzed protometabolic chemistry described in Sources 9400. This provides \u03b1-KG (C5), the direct precursor to glutamate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ ions in solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"\u03b1-KG + NH3 + H2 \u2192 glutamate + H2O; reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C2 ketone of \u03b1-ketoglutarate (HOOC-CO-CH2-CH2-COOH) condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base). The C=N double bond is then reduced by H2 (or Fe2+/FeS-donated electrons) to give the amine, yielding glutamate. This is a standard reductive amination. Carbon count preserved: C5 \u2192 C5.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids is one of the most fundamental prebiotic reactions (Bada, 2013; Sources 9396, 9334). The conversion of \u03b1-KG to glutamate by reductive amination with NH3 has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Kitadai & Maruyama, 2018). Fe2+ facilitates the reduction. This is the biological pathway in reverse of glutamate dehydrogenase.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate partial reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0/FeS mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Selective reduction of C5-carboxylate to aldehyde; HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-COOH + 2[H] \u2192 HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO + H2O\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxylate group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the Fe0 surface. The \u03b1-carboxylate is less accessible due to the adjacent amino group providing steric/electronic differentiation. Fe0 donates electrons, and the reaction proceeds through a hemiacetal intermediate. This is the prebiotically most challenging step in this pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In biology, this step is performed by \u03b3-glutamyl kinase + \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase (using ATP + NADPH). Prebiotically, Fe0 provides sufficient reducing potential (E\u00b0 = -0.44 V) for carboxylate-to-aldehyde reduction. The reaction is endergonic in solution but is driven by Fe0 oxidation. Similar mineral-surface carboxylate reductions have been proposed by Huber & Wachtershauser (1997, 2006). This is explicitly acknowledged as the rate-limiting step of this pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required; spontaneous\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Intramolecular imine formation; loss of H2O\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The free amino group at C2 of glutamate-5-semialdehyde attacks the C5 aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a 5-membered ring with an imine (C=N) bond. One equivalent of water is lost. This Schiff base cyclization is spontaneous and thermodynamically favorable due to the stability of the 5-membered ring. Product is \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C is well-documented in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically in aqueous solution (Adams & Frank, 1980). This is the key ring-closure step that forms the pyrrolidine skeleton of proline. The reaction has no kinetic barrier and proceeds at room temperature, making it highly prebiotically plausible.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to L-Proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/FeS as electron donor; or borohydride analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"P5C + 2[H] \u2192 Proline; imine reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is reduced to a C-N single bond by 2-electron reduction. H2 or Fe2+/sulfide-donated electrons provide the reducing equivalents. This converts the cyclic imine to a pyrrolidine, yielding proline. In biology this is catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADH-dependent). Prebiotically, imine reduction is thermodynamically favorable with mineral reductants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Imine reduction is one of the most thermodynamically favorable reductions in aqueous solution and occurs readily with mild reductants. Fe2+/H2S systems can provide the required electrons (Barge et al., 2019). The non-enzymatic reduction of P5C to proline has been discussed in the context of prebiotic amino acid synthesis. Levine et al. (2008) demonstrated enantioselective synthesis and amplification of amino acids including proline under prebiotic conditions (Sources 15388). Racemic proline is the expected prebiotic product; enantiomeric excess may arise from secondary amplification processes (Sources 21298).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Mannich-type cyclization of glycine with formaldehyde to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite; acid/base from mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H2NCH2COOH + 3 CH2O + 2 H2 \u2192 C5H9NO2 + 3 H2O; Mannich-type sequential addition and cyclization; wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Glycine + CH2O \u2192 N-methyleneglycine (Schiff base, H2C=N-CH2-COOH + H2O). Step 2: Mannich addition of second CH2O to the N-methyleneglycine \u2192 N,N-bis(hydroxymethyl)glycine or equivalent 3-carbon chain on nitrogen. Step 3: Third CH2O Mannich addition extends chain to 5-carbon skeleton. Step 4: Intramolecular cyclization forms the pyrrolidine ring. Step 5: Reduction of imine/hemiaminal intermediates by H2. Net stoichiometry: Glycine (C2) + 3 CH2O (3\u00d7C1) + 2H2 \u2192 Proline (C5) + 3H2O. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and templates the cyclization. Wet-dry cycling drives dehydration steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reaction of formaldehyde with glycine to produce proline, sarcosine, and betaine is documented experimentally under prebiotic conditions (Sources 2595). The stoichiometry requires 3 equivalents of CH2O to account for the C2\u2192C5 carbon increase, plus 2 H2 as reductant to balance hydrogen (correcting the stoichiometry error noted in the previous attempt). Montmorillonite catalyzes polymerization and Mannich-type reactions (Sources 9431). This represents the most direct experimentally supported route to proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde + ammonia cyclization to \u03941-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO + NH3 \u2192 \u03941-pyrroline + H2O; imine formation + intramolecular cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH3 attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine. The terminal amino group then attacks the second aldehyde intramolecularly to form the 5-membered ring, losing a second H2O. Net: C4H6O2 + NH3 \u2192 C4H7N + 2H2O. The 5-membered ring is thermodynamically stable.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of dialdehydes with amines is a well-known reaction in organic chemistry. Formation of \u03941-pyrroline from succinaldehyde and ammonia is the basis of the Knorr pyrrole synthesis and related reactions. Under prebiotic conditions, this provides the cyclic imine scaffold for the proline aminonitrile route. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and promotes dehydration.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN addition to \u03941-pyrroline: proline aminonitrile formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface; slightly basic pH\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Strecker-type: cyclic imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile (cyclic)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CN- (from HCN deprotonation) attacks the electrophilic C=N carbon of \u03941-pyrroline. The nucleophilic addition forms pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (proline aminonitrile). This is a Strecker-type addition of cyanide to a cyclic imine, forming the C-CN bond that will become the carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker addition of HCN to imines is the classic pathway for prebiotic aminonitrile formation (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Sources 21189, 10835). Sources 22185 specifically describe the unique behavior of proline aminonitrile under prebiotic conditions, indicating this intermediate has been experimentally characterized. The cyclic imine substrate provides direct access to the cyclic amino acid.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline aminonitrile hydrolysis to proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none; aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"C5H8N2 + 2H2O \u2192 C5H9NO2 + NH3; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of proline aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: CN + H2O \u2192 CONH2 (amide) + H2O \u2192 COOH (carboxylic acid) + NH3. The pyrrolidine ring is stable under these conditions. Product is racemic proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid is a standard aqueous reaction that occurs under mildly acidic or basic conditions and at elevated temperatures. This is the final step of the Strecker synthesis. Sources 22185 discuss proline aminonitrile behavior, noting its unique properties compared to other aminonitriles. Hydrolysis completes the conversion to proline.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-surface Mannich route (CO2 origin)\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete CO2-to-proline pathway via hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate, reduction to formaldehyde, surface Strecker synthesis to glycine, then Mannich cyclization with 3 additional formaldehyde + H2 reductant to proline. This is the most experimentally supported route (Sources 2595).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"HKG cycle biological-analog route (pyruvate + glyoxylate \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline)\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate (from hydrothermal CO2 fixation) and glyoxylate undergo aldol condensation (HKG cycle) to form \u03b1-KG (C3+C2=C5). \u03b1-KG is reductively aminated to glutamate, which is partially reduced to GSA, spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline. This mimics the biological proline biosynthesis pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile-to-glycine Mannich route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine (cyanosulfidic pathway), then glycine + 3 CH2O + 2H2 \u2192 proline via Mannich cyclization. This variant uses the glycolonitrile intermediate rather than direct Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker glycine to Mannich proline (surface-only short route)\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest route using pre-existing formaldehyde and HCN. Formaldehyde acts as both Strecker aldehyde for glycine synthesis and as Mannich reagent for ring closure. All reactions occur in surface evaporitic pool environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline aminonitrile route via hydrothermal \u03b1-KG decarboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-KG (from HKG cycle) undergoes thermal decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde (C5\u2192C4), which is reduced to succinaldehyde on Fe0, cyclizes with NH3 to \u03941-pyrroline, then Strecker addition of HCN gives proline aminonitrile, hydrolysis yields proline. This is the most chemically distinct pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-to-pyruvate carboxylation pathway to proline via glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate (Wood-Ljungdahl analog) \u2192 pyruvate (carboxylation) \u2192 \u03b1-KG (HKG cycle) \u2192 glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. This route emphasizes the acetyl-CoA pathway analog for C2 production.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_023\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-glyoxylate convergent pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde (formose) \u2192 glyoxylate (UV photocatalysis on TiO2) \u2192 combines with pyruvate in HKG aldol \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. This route generates glyoxylate from surface photochemistry rather than hydrothermal carboxylation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Proline aminonitrile route via formose-photochemistry glyoxylate\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-origin glyoxylate (from glycolaldehyde UV oxidation) enters HKG cycle to make \u03b1-KG, which is decarboxylated and reduced to succinaldehyde, cyclized with NH3, and converted to proline via Strecker aminonitrile pathway. Combines surface photochemistry with hydrothermal reductive chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO2 fixation to pyruvate, then biological-analog proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Most direct hydrothermal route: CO2 + H2 \u2192 pyruvate on greigite/magnetite (one-pot), then surface/biochemical HKG cycle steps to proline. Bypasses formate/formaldehyde intermediates. Pyruvate is the key hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetate-pyruvate proline aminonitrile convergent route\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines Wood-Ljungdahl-type acetate synthesis (rxn_005) with carboxylation to pyruvate, HKG cycle to \u03b1-KG, then branches through the proline aminonitrile route (decarboxylation \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 \u03941-pyrroline \u2192 Strecker \u2192 proline). Maximum environmental diversity.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_021\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - central C1 hub formed hydrothermally, consumed in 5 surface reactions\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycine - formed via 2 independent surface routes (direct Strecker, glycolonitrile), consumed in Mannich proline synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylate - formed by 2 independent routes (hydrothermal carboxylation, surface photocatalysis), consumed in HKG aldol\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate - formed by 2 routes (direct CO2 fixation, acetate carboxylation), consumed in HKG aldol to \u03b1-KG\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate - the critical C5 hub formed by HKG cycle aldol, feeds both the glutamate-P5C route and the proline aminonitrile route\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C (\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate) - direct precursor to proline via reduction; formed by GSA spontaneous cyclization\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "L-Proline (C5H9NO2) is a cyclic amino acid whose prebiotic synthesis requires assembly of a pyrrolidine ring from smaller precursors. The network pursues three complementary strategies grounded in literature: (1) A Mannich-type route from glycine + 3 formaldehyde + reductant (Sources 2595), requiring proper C2+3C1=C5 stoichiometry with H2 as reductant; (2) A biological-analog route via \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA) \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline, where \u03b1-KG is formed by aldol condensation of pyruvate (C3) + glyoxylate (C2) following the HKG cycle (Sources 10738); and (3) A proline aminonitrile route via \u03941-pyrroline + HCN (Sources 22185), where \u03941-pyrroline derives from succinaldehyde + NH3, and succinaldehyde is formed by Fe0-catalyzed reduction of \u03b1-KG decarboxylation product succinic semialdehyde. Hub molecules (formaldehyde, glycine, pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, P5C) create convergence points linking hydrothermal CO2 fixation, surface Strecker/Mannich chemistry, and biochemical cyclization/reduction steps.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "Glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "Glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "Glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-Ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "Glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H7NO3", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-Proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "4-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "Succinic semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "Succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H7N", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "Delta-1-pyrroline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "Proline aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "4-Hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate (HKG)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "CH3COO-", "iupac_name": "acetate", "common_name": "Acetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on the greigite surface. H2 dissociates on FeNiS sites. Hydride transfer to CO2 produces formate (HCOO-). This mirrors the first step of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway catalyzed by formate dehydrogenase, whose active site resembles greigite.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on iron-sulfur minerals is one of the best-characterized prebiotic carbon fixation reactions. Greigite (Fe3S4) is a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters and catalyzes this reaction under hydrothermal conditions (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). This is the entry point for all carbon into the network. Sources 9400 describe Fe2+-catalyzed reactions producing key metabolic precursors at 70\u00b0C."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite with Fe0", "aqueous": true, "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal, rock-water interactions, strongly reducing"}, "mechanism": "Formate is reduced to formaldehyde via 2-electron reduction. Fe0 acts as the electron donor, being oxidized to Fe2+. Magnetite surface provides the catalytic platform for H-transfer. HCOO- + 2[H] \u2192 CH2O + H2O.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction of formate to formaldehyde on magnetite surfaces has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom et al., 1999; He et al., 2019). Fe0 provides the thermodynamic driving force. Formaldehyde is an essential C1 building block. Sources 2595 require formaldehyde concentrations of ~30 mM for amino acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate carboxylation to glyoxylate on iron minerals", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent, CO2-rich fluids mixing with H2-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "Formate undergoes carboxylation via CO2 insertion on the pyrite surface. The activated C1 formate attacks CO2 to form the C2 \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate (OHCCOOH). FeS clusters provide electron density to activate CO2.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a key C2 \u03b1-keto acid required for the HKG cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017; Sources 10738). Pyrite-mediated carboxylation reactions have been proposed in the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (Wachtershauser, 1988). CO2 fixation into C-C bonds on metal sulfide surfaces is a core feature of hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "CO2 reductive fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite + magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "3 CO2 + 4 H2 \u2192 pyruvate + 3 H2O; alkaline vent, native iron present"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on greigite/magnetite surfaces. CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO (or formyl intermediate) \u2192 acetyl intermediate \u2192 pyruvate via further CO2 insertion. Each step involves H2-driven reduction on the mineral surface. Net: 3CO2 + 4H2 \u2192 CH3COCOOH + 3H2O.", "reasoning": "Direct CO2-to-pyruvate synthesis on iron minerals has been demonstrated by Varma et al. (2018) and Muchowska et al. (2019). Greigite provides the catalytic surface mimicking the acetyl-CoA pathway. This is a cornerstone of the 'metabolism-first' hypothesis. Sources 9400 describe Fe2+-catalyzed formation of metabolic precursors including pyruvate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Formate to acetate on greigite (acetyl-CoA pathway analog)", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_023", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (FeNiS)", "aqueous": true, "other": "2 HCOO- + 2 H2 \u2192 CH3COO- + 2 H2O; Wood-Ljungdahl analog"}, "mechanism": "Two formate molecules undergo reductive coupling on greigite surface. First formate is reduced to a methyl group, second is reduced to CO, then carbonyl insertion forms the acetyl group which is hydrolyzed to acetate. 2HCOO- + 2H2 \u2192 CH3COO- + OH- + H2O.", "reasoning": "Acetate synthesis from CO2/formate on FeNiS minerals mimics the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway and has been demonstrated under hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020; Herschy et al., 2014). This provides an alternative C2 building block feeding into pyruvate synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Acetate carboxylation to pyruvate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_023", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite with Fe0 reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "CH3COO- + CO2 + 2[H] \u2192 CH3COCOO- + H2O; reductive carboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Acetate undergoes reductive carboxylation at the methyl C-H bond. CO2 inserts via a metal-carboxylate intermediate on the pyrite surface. Fe0 provides electrons for the reductive activation. Product is pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Reductive carboxylation of acetate to pyruvate on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed as a key step in the reverse/reductive TCA cycle analog (Wachtershauser, 1990; Muchowska et al., 2019). Sources 9400 report Fe2+-catalyzed formation of pyruvate-related intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "\u03b1-KG decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acid; C5 \u2192 C4 + CO2"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (HOOC-CO-CH2-CH2-COOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the C1 position adjacent to the keto group. The \u03b2-keto acid motif facilitates loss of CO2, yielding succinic semialdehyde (OHC-CH2-CH2-COOH). Pyrite surface stabilizes the transition state.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is well-established in prebiotic chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures. This is the non-enzymatic analog of the \u03b1-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase reaction. In biology, this produces succinyl-CoA; prebiotically, the product is succinic semialdehyde. The \u03b2-keto acid decarboxylation is thermodynamically favorable (Guzman & Martin, 2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Succinic semialdehyde reduction to succinaldehyde on Fe0", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe0 surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "OHC-CH2-CH2-COOH + 2[H] \u2192 OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO + H2O; carboxylate reduction on native iron"}, "mechanism": "Succinic semialdehyde adsorbs on the Fe0 surface via the carboxylate group. Fe0 donates 2 electrons and H+ is provided by water. The carboxylate is reduced through a hemiacetal-like intermediate to the aldehyde. Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ provides the thermodynamic driving force (\u0394G << 0 for Fe0 oxidation). Net: RCOOH + 2[H] \u2192 RCHO + H2O.", "reasoning": "Carboxylate reduction to aldehyde is thermodynamically challenging in solution but becomes feasible on Fe0 surfaces due to the highly negative reduction potential of Fe0/Fe2+ (-0.44 V). Fe0 is present in hydrothermal systems from meteoritic iron and serpentinization products. Carboxylate reduction on metal surfaces under hydrothermal conditions has been discussed by Huber & Wachtershauser (2006) and is thermodynamically driven by the strong reducing capacity of native iron. This is the rate-limiting step of the proline aminonitrile pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Formaldehyde-HCN coupling to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "Neutral to slightly basic pH; cyanohydrin formation"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of CN- to formaldehyde carbonyl. HCN deprotonates in slightly basic conditions to give CN-, which attacks CH2O to form glycolonitrile (HOCH2CN). Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants via adsorption.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN is a well-established prebiotic reaction and is central to the cyanosulfidic scenario (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016). Sources 9376, 16400 identify glycolonitrile as a critical precursor in prebiotic amino acid synthesis. This is one of the most robust prebiotic reactions known."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Glycolonitrile hydrolysis and amination to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous solution, NH3 present; nitrile hydrolysis + aminonitrile pathway"}, "mechanism": "Glycolonitrile (HOCH2CN) undergoes aminolysis: NH3 displaces OH to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN). Subsequent hydrolysis of the nitrile group (CN \u2192 CONH2 \u2192 COOH) yields glycine. Montmorillonite catalyzes the hydrolysis step. This is a modified Strecker pathway where the aminonitrile intermediate is formed via the glycolonitrile route.", "reasoning": "The glycolonitrile-to-glycine pathway via aminonitrile intermediates is well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376, 16400, 6942). The Strecker reaction (aldehyde + NH3 + HCN \u2192 amino acid) is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Sources 6940, 21189). Montmorillonite facilitates hydrolysis and concentrates reactants (Sources 9431)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Classical Strecker: CH2O + NH3 + HCN \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 hydrolysis \u2192 glycine"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Formaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form the imine H2C=NH. Step 2: HCN adds to the imine to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN). Step 3: Nitrile hydrolysis in water yields glycine. CH2O + NH3 + HCN + H2O \u2192 H2NCH2COOH + NH3 (regenerated from HCN hydrolysis byproduct).", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the most well-characterized prebiotic amino acid formation reactions (Miller, 1953; Strecker, 1850; Sources 6940, 6942, 21189, 10835). It has been demonstrated under a variety of simulated prebiotic conditions including spark discharge experiments, hydrothermal fluids, and surface evaporitic pools. The direct Strecker route to glycine from CH2O is the simplest and most robust pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Formose-type aldol to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2 or borate", "aqueous": true, "other": "2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO; base-catalyzed formose reaction first step"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The Cannizzaro disproportionation provides the initial enolizable species. Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals act as base. Borate stabilizes the glycolaldehyde product against further aldol reactions by forming borate esters. 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a classic prebiotic reaction (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products and prevent tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004; Sources reference formose reaction with borate). This provides C2 aldehyde building blocks for further synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Glycolaldehyde oxidation to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV photocatalytic oxidation; HOCH2CHO \u2192 OHCCOOH + 2[H]; anoxic but UV-driven"}, "mechanism": "TiO2 absorbs UV light generating electron-hole pairs. The hole oxidizes glycolaldehyde at the alcohol group: HOCH2CHO \u2192 OHC-COOH (glyoxylate). Under anoxic conditions, Fe3+ or the TiO2 hole serves as the terminal electron acceptor. This provides a surface-environment route to glyoxylate complementing the hydrothermal carboxylation route (rxn_003).", "reasoning": "TiO2 photocatalytic oxidation of organic molecules under UV irradiation is well-established in prebiotic surface chemistry. Early Earth lacked an ozone layer, providing intense UV for photocatalysis. This provides a convergent route to glyoxylate (also formed hydrothermally in rxn_003), creating a key convergence point in the network."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol to 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate (HKG)", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite; Fe2+ in solution", "aqueous": true, "other": "CH3COCOO- (C3) + OHCCOO- (C2) \u2192 HKG (C5); aldol condensation"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate (C3) and glyoxylate (C2) undergo aldol condensation. The enolizable methyl group of pyruvate attacks the aldehyde of glyoxylate. This forms 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate (HKG, C5), the signature intermediate of the HKG cycle. Fe2+ or montmorillonite Lewis acid sites catalyze the aldol. Carbon balance: C3 + C2 = C5 \u2713.", "reasoning": "This aldol condensation is the central reaction of the Hydroxy Ketoglutarate (HKG) cycle demonstrated by Muchowska et al. (2017, 2019) and described in Sources 10738, 10732, 9988. The HKG cycle provides a prebiotically plausible analog of the TCA cycle. Pyruvate + glyoxylate \u2192 HKG is one of the most robust prebiotic C-C bond forming reactions, with proper C3 + C2 = C5 stoichiometry."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "HKG dehydration/reduction to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+ in solution", "aqueous": true, "other": "HKG \u2192 \u03b1-KG via dehydration then reduction of double bond; Fe2+ as electron source"}, "mechanism": "4-Hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate undergoes dehydration to form 2-oxoglutaconate (elimination of H2O from the 3,4-hydroxyl). Then the resulting double bond is reduced by Fe2+-donated electrons (or H2) to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Net: HKG + 2[H] \u2192 \u03b1-KG + H2O.", "reasoning": "The conversion of HKG to \u03b1-KG via dehydration-reduction is part of the HKG cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017, 2019; Sources 10738). Fe2+ serves as the electron donor for the reduction step, consistent with the Fe2+-catalyzed protometabolic chemistry described in Sources 9400. This provides \u03b1-KG (C5), the direct precursor to glutamate."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+ ions in solution", "aqueous": true, "other": "\u03b1-KG + NH3 + H2 \u2192 glutamate + H2O; reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "The C2 ketone of \u03b1-ketoglutarate (HOOC-CO-CH2-CH2-COOH) condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base). The C=N double bond is then reduced by H2 (or Fe2+/FeS-donated electrons) to give the amine, yielding glutamate. This is a standard reductive amination. Carbon count preserved: C5 \u2192 C5.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids is one of the most fundamental prebiotic reactions (Bada, 2013; Sources 9396, 9334). The conversion of \u03b1-KG to glutamate by reductive amination with NH3 has been demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Kitadai & Maruyama, 2018). Fe2+ facilitates the reduction. This is the biological pathway in reverse of glutamate dehydrogenase."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Glutamate partial reduction to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (GSA)", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe0/FeS mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Selective reduction of C5-carboxylate to aldehyde; HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-COOH + 2[H] \u2192 HOOC-CH(NH2)-CH2-CH2-CHO + H2O"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxylate group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the Fe0 surface. The \u03b1-carboxylate is less accessible due to the adjacent amino group providing steric/electronic differentiation. Fe0 donates electrons, and the reaction proceeds through a hemiacetal intermediate. This is the prebiotically most challenging step in this pathway.", "reasoning": "In biology, this step is performed by \u03b3-glutamyl kinase + \u03b3-glutamyl phosphate reductase (using ATP + NADPH). Prebiotically, Fe0 provides sufficient reducing potential (E\u00b0 = -0.44 V) for carboxylate-to-aldehyde reduction. The reaction is endergonic in solution but is driven by Fe0 oxidation. Similar mineral-surface carboxylate reductions have been proposed by Huber & Wachtershauser (1997, 2006). This is explicitly acknowledged as the rate-limiting step of this pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required; spontaneous", "aqueous": true, "other": "Intramolecular imine formation; loss of H2O"}, "mechanism": "The free amino group at C2 of glutamate-5-semialdehyde attacks the C5 aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a 5-membered ring with an imine (C=N) bond. One equivalent of water is lost. This Schiff base cyclization is spontaneous and thermodynamically favorable due to the stability of the 5-membered ring. Product is \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C).", "reasoning": "The spontaneous cyclization of GSA to P5C is well-documented in biochemistry and occurs non-enzymatically in aqueous solution (Adams & Frank, 1980). This is the key ring-closure step that forms the pyrrolidine skeleton of proline. The reaction has no kinetic barrier and proceeds at room temperature, making it highly prebiotically plausible."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Reduction of P5C to L-Proline", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+/FeS as electron donor; or borohydride analog", "aqueous": true, "other": "P5C + 2[H] \u2192 Proline; imine reduction"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is reduced to a C-N single bond by 2-electron reduction. H2 or Fe2+/sulfide-donated electrons provide the reducing equivalents. This converts the cyclic imine to a pyrrolidine, yielding proline. In biology this is catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADH-dependent). Prebiotically, imine reduction is thermodynamically favorable with mineral reductants.", "reasoning": "Imine reduction is one of the most thermodynamically favorable reductions in aqueous solution and occurs readily with mild reductants. Fe2+/H2S systems can provide the required electrons (Barge et al., 2019). The non-enzymatic reduction of P5C to proline has been discussed in the context of prebiotic amino acid synthesis. Levine et al. (2008) demonstrated enantioselective synthesis and amplification of amino acids including proline under prebiotic conditions (Sources 15388). Racemic proline is the expected prebiotic product; enantiomeric excess may arise from secondary amplification processes (Sources 21298)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Mannich-type cyclization of glycine with formaldehyde to proline", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite; acid/base from mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "H2NCH2COOH + 3 CH2O + 2 H2 \u2192 C5H9NO2 + 3 H2O; Mannich-type sequential addition and cyclization; wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Glycine + CH2O \u2192 N-methyleneglycine (Schiff base, H2C=N-CH2-COOH + H2O). Step 2: Mannich addition of second CH2O to the N-methyleneglycine \u2192 N,N-bis(hydroxymethyl)glycine or equivalent 3-carbon chain on nitrogen. Step 3: Third CH2O Mannich addition extends chain to 5-carbon skeleton. Step 4: Intramolecular cyclization forms the pyrrolidine ring. Step 5: Reduction of imine/hemiaminal intermediates by H2. Net stoichiometry: Glycine (C2) + 3 CH2O (3\u00d7C1) + 2H2 \u2192 Proline (C5) + 3H2O. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and templates the cyclization. Wet-dry cycling drives dehydration steps.", "reasoning": "The reaction of formaldehyde with glycine to produce proline, sarcosine, and betaine is documented experimentally under prebiotic conditions (Sources 2595). The stoichiometry requires 3 equivalents of CH2O to account for the C2\u2192C5 carbon increase, plus 2 H2 as reductant to balance hydrogen (correcting the stoichiometry error noted in the previous attempt). Montmorillonite catalyzes polymerization and Mannich-type reactions (Sources 9431). This represents the most direct experimentally supported route to proline."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Succinaldehyde + ammonia cyclization to \u03941-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO + NH3 \u2192 \u03941-pyrroline + H2O; imine formation + intramolecular cyclization"}, "mechanism": "NH3 attacks one aldehyde of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine. The terminal amino group then attacks the second aldehyde intramolecularly to form the 5-membered ring, losing a second H2O. Net: C4H6O2 + NH3 \u2192 C4H7N + 2H2O. The 5-membered ring is thermodynamically stable.", "reasoning": "Intramolecular cyclization of dialdehydes with amines is a well-known reaction in organic chemistry. Formation of \u03941-pyrroline from succinaldehyde and ammonia is the basis of the Knorr pyrrole synthesis and related reactions. Under prebiotic conditions, this provides the cyclic imine scaffold for the proline aminonitrile route. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and promotes dehydration."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "HCN addition to \u03941-pyrroline: proline aminonitrile formation", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface; slightly basic pH", "aqueous": true, "other": "Strecker-type: cyclic imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile (cyclic)"}, "mechanism": "CN- (from HCN deprotonation) attacks the electrophilic C=N carbon of \u03941-pyrroline. The nucleophilic addition forms pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (proline aminonitrile). This is a Strecker-type addition of cyanide to a cyclic imine, forming the C-CN bond that will become the carboxylate.", "reasoning": "The Strecker addition of HCN to imines is the classic pathway for prebiotic aminonitrile formation (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Sources 21189, 10835). Sources 22185 specifically describe the unique behavior of proline aminonitrile under prebiotic conditions, indicating this intermediate has been experimentally characterized. The cyclic imine substrate provides direct access to the cyclic amino acid."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Proline aminonitrile hydrolysis to proline", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none; aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "C5H8N2 + 2H2O \u2192 C5H9NO2 + NH3; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-CN) of proline aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: CN + H2O \u2192 CONH2 (amide) + H2O \u2192 COOH (carboxylic acid) + NH3. The pyrrolidine ring is stable under these conditions. Product is racemic proline.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid is a standard aqueous reaction that occurs under mildly acidic or basic conditions and at elevated temperatures. This is the final step of the Strecker synthesis. Sources 22185 discuss proline aminonitrile behavior, noting its unique properties compared to other aminonitriles. Hydrolysis completes the conversion to proline."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full hydrothermal-to-surface Mannich route (CO2 origin)", "description": "Complete CO2-to-proline pathway via hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate, reduction to formaldehyde, surface Strecker synthesis to glycine, then Mannich cyclization with 3 additional formaldehyde + H2 reductant to proline. This is the most experimentally supported route (Sources 2595).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "HKG cycle biological-analog route (pyruvate + glyoxylate \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline)", "description": "Pyruvate (from hydrothermal CO2 fixation) and glyoxylate undergo aldol condensation (HKG cycle) to form \u03b1-KG (C3+C2=C5). \u03b1-KG is reductively aminated to glutamate, which is partially reduced to GSA, spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline. This mimics the biological proline biosynthesis pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile-to-glycine Mannich route", "description": "Formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine (cyanosulfidic pathway), then glycine + 3 CH2O + 2H2 \u2192 proline via Mannich cyclization. This variant uses the glycolonitrile intermediate rather than direct Strecker synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Direct Strecker glycine to Mannich proline (surface-only short route)", "description": "Shortest route using pre-existing formaldehyde and HCN. Formaldehyde acts as both Strecker aldehyde for glycine synthesis and as Mannich reagent for ring closure. All reactions occur in surface evaporitic pool environment.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Proline aminonitrile route via hydrothermal \u03b1-KG decarboxylation", "description": "\u03b1-KG (from HKG cycle) undergoes thermal decarboxylation to succinic semialdehyde (C5\u2192C4), which is reduced to succinaldehyde on Fe0, cyclizes with NH3 to \u03941-pyrroline, then Strecker addition of HCN gives proline aminonitrile, hydrolysis yields proline. This is the most chemically distinct pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_021"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Acetate-to-pyruvate carboxylation pathway to proline via glutamate", "description": "CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate (Wood-Ljungdahl analog) \u2192 pyruvate (carboxylation) \u2192 \u03b1-KG (HKG cycle) \u2192 glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. This route emphasizes the acetyl-CoA pathway analog for C2 production.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_023", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formose-glyoxylate convergent pathway", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde (formose) \u2192 glyoxylate (UV photocatalysis on TiO2) \u2192 combines with pyruvate in HKG aldol \u2192 \u03b1-KG \u2192 glutamate \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. This route generates glyoxylate from surface photochemistry rather than hydrothermal carboxylation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_004", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Proline aminonitrile route via formose-photochemistry glyoxylate", "description": "Surface-origin glyoxylate (from glycolaldehyde UV oxidation) enters HKG cycle to make \u03b1-KG, which is decarboxylated and reduced to succinaldehyde, cyclized with NH3, and converted to proline via Strecker aminonitrile pathway. Combines surface photochemistry with hydrothermal reductive chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_004", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Direct CO2 fixation to pyruvate, then biological-analog proline", "description": "Most direct hydrothermal route: CO2 + H2 \u2192 pyruvate on greigite/magnetite (one-pot), then surface/biochemical HKG cycle steps to proline. Bypasses formate/formaldehyde intermediates. Pyruvate is the key hub.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Acetate-pyruvate proline aminonitrile convergent route", "description": "Combines Wood-Ljungdahl-type acetate synthesis (rxn_005) with carboxylation to pyruvate, HKG cycle to \u03b1-KG, then branches through the proline aminonitrile route (decarboxylation \u2192 succinaldehyde \u2192 \u03941-pyrroline \u2192 Strecker \u2192 proline). Maximum environmental diversity.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_023", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_019", "mol_021"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_016"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde - central C1 hub formed hydrothermally, consumed in 5 surface reactions", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_020"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Glycine - formed via 2 independent surface routes (direct Strecker, glycolonitrile), consumed in Mannich proline synthesis", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_020"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Glyoxylate - formed by 2 independent routes (hydrothermal carboxylation, surface photocatalysis), consumed in HKG aldol", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_0